  "difficulty": "Advanced",
  "tips": [
    "Apply penetrating oil to all exhaust nuts before removal as they are usually rusty",
    "Use a shallow 12mm 1/4 inch socket on a swivel with a 1/4 inch extension, then an adapter to 3/8 and a 3/8 extension and ratchet to reach all passenger side exhaust manifold nuts",
    "Make sure the socket isn't so shallow that it doesn't clear over the stud, or it won't grab the nut fully and may round it off",
    "The two most challenging nuts are the top front nut and the one second from the front on the top row",
    "Clean the cylinder head mating surface with a sharp razor blade then smooth with a scour pad — do not use a grinder or power wheel as it can damage the aluminum and cause exhaust leaks",
    "The manifold is steel so a grinder or wire wheel can be used on it carefully, but avoid aggressive sandpaper wheels",
    "Remove the bolt holding the transmission coolant pipes to gain access to the top 14mm starter bolt",
    "The starter may be stuck and require gentle prying to remove",
    "Remove the small heat shield nuts to make exhaust manifold removal easier",
    "Plug in the single wire connector before installing the main 12mm starter terminal nut"
  ],
